'''Terrance "Terry" Sweeney''' (born March 23, 1950){{citation needed|date=October 2012}} is an American writer, comedian and actor. He was a writer and cast member of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' in the 1980s, co-wrote the 1989 film ''[[Shag (film)|Shag]]'', and has written for the television ''series [[Mad TV|MADtv]]'', ''[[Hype (TV series)|Hype]]'', and ''[[Tripping the Rift]]''.
== Early life and career == Terrence (Terry) Sweeney was born in 1950<!-- Not 1960; that would put him graduating high school at the age of 9 and university at 13. --> in [[Queens]], New York and raised in [[Massapequa Park, New York]] as the younger of two children to Terrence, a butcher, and Lenore Sweeney.<ref name="people-june1986">{{cite news|last=Hutchings|first=David|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20093779,00.html|title=Terry Sweeney Opens Some Eyes, and Maybe a Few Minds, as Saturday Night Live's First Lady|date=1986-06-02|publisher=people.com|accessdate=2012-11-18}}</ref> As a child, he was bullied and found solace in books, including the [[Nancy Drew]] mysteries, as well as in performing his own Broadway plays.<ref name="people-june1986" /> At a young age, his interest in the performing arts grew.<ref name="splitsider-2012">{{cite web|last=Wright|first=Megh|url=http://splitsider.com/2012/04/saturday-nights-children-terry-sweeney-1985-1986/|title=Saturday Night's Children: Terry Sweeney (1985-1986)|date=2012-04-12|publisher=splitsider.com|accessdate=2012-11-18}}</ref> He graduated Farmingdale High School in 1969 and attended [[Middlebury College]], where he learned Spanish and Italian and graduated in 1973 with a bachelor of arts degree.<ref name="people-june1986" /> In his sophomore year, he got engaged to a woman, even though he had started identifying himself as [[gay]] by the fourth grade.<ref name="people-june1986" /> Before becoming a writer, he worked as a drug rehabilitation counselor and waiter.<ref name="people-june1986" />
=== ''Saturday Night Live'' === Sweeney is best known for his appearances as a regular cast member of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (''SNL'') during that program's 1985â€“86 season. He was discovered by series producer [[Lorne Michaels]] while Sweeney was performing in a New York play,<ref name="dailynews-losangeles">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF5BA1F2EF8E466&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=COMEDY NEWS & NOTES|date=February 9, 1990|publisher=''Daily News of Los Angeles''|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> ''Banned in France,'' in 1983.<ref name="people-june1986" /> Sweeney, who is not related to fellow ''SNL'' alumna [[Julia Sweeney]], was also a sketch writer for ''SNL'' during the early 1980s under producer [[Jean Doumanian]] prior to being hired as a member of the cast.
He was ''SNL'''s first [[coming out|openly]] [[gay]] male cast member; Sweeney was "out" prior to being hired as a cast member.<ref name="shales">{{citation |title=Live from New York: An Uncensored History of Saturday Night Live |first=Tom |last=Shales |first2=James Andrew |last2=Miller |year=2002 |publisher=Back Bay |isbn=0-316-73565-5 |page=316}}</ref> Sweeney's run on the show came at a time when there were few openly gay characters or actors on television. For roughly 27 years, there were no other openly gay cast members on ''SNL'',<ref name="afterelton-2010">{{cite web|last=Hartinger|first=Brent|url=http://www.thebacklot.com/ask-the-flying-monkey-why-is-steel-magnolias-fabulous-or-is-it/11/2010/|title=Ask the Flying Monkey: Why Is "Steel Magnolias" Fabulous? (Or IS It?)|date=November 21, 2010|publisher=afterelton.com|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> until [[Kate McKinnon]] (a former cast member of Logo's ''The Big Gay Sketch Show'') was added to the cast in April 2012.
During his season on ''SNL'', he became known for his celebrity impersonations, particularly female impersonations of stars like [[Diana Ross]],<ref name="dailynews-losangeles" /> [[Patti LaBelle]],<ref name="dailynews-losangeles" /> [[Joan Collins]], [[Brooke Shields]]'s mother Teri Shields, and [[Joan Rivers]],<ref name="dailynews-losangeles" /> as well as [[Ted Kennedy]]<ref name="dailynews-losangeles" /> (the only male celebrity he impersonated). His most notable recurring character was a portrayal of then-First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]];<ref>{{cite news|last=Roush|first=Matt|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/55694835.html?dids=55694835:55694835&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+15%2C+1987&author=Matt+Roush&pub=USA+TODAY+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=Sweeney+will+drag+Nancy+along+to+%60The+Late+Show%27&pqatl=google|title=Sweeney will drag Nancy along to `The Late Show'|date=June 15, 1987|publisher=''USA Today''|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dyess-Nugent|first=Phil|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/distilling-4-decades-of-saturday-night-live-down-t,85102/|title=Distilling 4 decades of Saturday Night Live down to just 10 episodes|date=September 19, 2012|publisher=avclub.com|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> While at ''SNL'', he faced many hardships from both the writers and cast because of his sexuality, especially from [[Chevy Chase]].<ref name="splitsider-2012" /><ref name="shales" /> Sweeney was told by [[Ron Reagan]], who hosted one of that season's episodes, that he was "more like his mother than she is."
=== Other credits === Sweeney has written for the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX TV]] series ''[[MADtv]]'',<ref name="afterelton-2010" /> [[The WB Television Network|The WB]]'s short-lived sketch comedy series [[Hype (TV series)|''Hype'']] (and co-created),<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y2IEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=Terry+Sweeney+Saturday+Night+Live&source=bl&ots=gSoEbF4Rho&sig=-SO9JL_oTYIgH_G_rG9iYn2UTgk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1YB7UN6PLJPzqwGYsoCwCA&ved=0CDoQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Terry%20Sweeney%20Saturday%20Night%20Live&f=false ''Out'' Magazine, September 2000, p. 62]</ref> and [[Sci Fi Channel (United States)|Sci Fi Channel]]'s ''[[Tripping the Rift]]'',<ref name="afterelton-2010" /> among a few others, all with his partner, Lanier Laney. Sweeney's major film credit was as the co-screenwriter for the film ''[[Shag (1989 film)|Shag]]'', which was released in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|last=Holden|first=Stephen|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=950DEEDB143BF932A15754C0A96F948260|title=Movie Review - Shag The Movie (1988)|date=July 21, 1989|publisher=nytimes.com|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> Sweeney also performed a stand-up routine for the special ''Coming Out Party'' in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vary|first=Adam B.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RGUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=Terry+Sweeney+Saturday+Night+Live&source=bl&ots=9LUZmszH8J&sig=Rx7St4r2S_6ZKXfGtU6vHGYJYc8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1YB7UN6PLJPzqwGYsoCwCA&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=Terry%20Sweeney%20Saturday%20Night%20Live&f=false|title=I'll laugh if I want to|date=October 14, 2003|publisher=''The Advocate''|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> In 2018 he appeared in two episodes of FX's ''[[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story]]'' as David Gallo.
=== Episodes of ''Tripping the Rift'' written by Sweeney and Laney === *"Mutilation Ball" (also written with Sy Rosen) *"Power to the Peephole" *"Android Love" *"Roswell" *"Creaturepalooza" *"Chode's Near-Death Experience" *"Six, Lies, and Videotape"
== Personal life == Terry Sweeney's partner is Lanier Laney, a comedy writer who also wrote for ''SNL'' in the 1985â€“1986 season.<ref name="afterelton-2010" /> According to a 2000 magazine article, they first met as members of a sketch comedy troupe called the "Bess Truman Players" before joining ''SNL''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goodridge|first=Mike|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wGMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA89&lpg=PA89&dq=Terry+Sweeney+Saturday+Night+Live&source=bl&ots=2dZYYXxtZm&sig=ouMrf33hbONwxHNwWRhWlPMpvS0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1YB7UN6PLJPzqwGYsoCwCA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Terry%20Sweeney%20Saturday%20Night%20Live&f=false|title=Believe the hype|date=October 24, 2000|publisher=''The Advocate''|accessdate=October 15, 2012}}</ref> Laney and Sweeney were also writing partners for ''Saturday Night Live'' during the 1985â€“1986 season, the film ''[[Shag (film)|Shag]]'', and the [[Syfy]] Channel cartoon ''Tripping The Rift''. As of 2012, the couple reside in [[Beaufort, South Carolina]].<ref name="splitsider-2012" />
